"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772041","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-25","<p>Cell 88 of HM Revenue and Customs Senior Officials’ Travel Report for the period 1 January to 31 March 2017 refers to eight rail bookings made by Senior Civil Servants travelling on official business between London, and Stafford, York, Durham, Southend, Newcastle, and Wolverhampton (via Birmingham and Telford).</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-25T13:43:24.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772041/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772041/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-17","Revenue and Customs: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to HM Revenue and Customs Senior Officials' travel return list of 1 January to 31 March 2017, published on 17 October 2017, what journeys the eight 1st class/mixed bookings in cell 88 of the spreadsheet refer to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772043","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Treasury does not hold data on the annual flow of remittances sent from the UK to other countries. The Office for National Statistics (ONS) produces data on UK transfers, which includes estimates for remittances alongside estimates for net transfers from UK charities, defined in the UK Balance of Payments (the Pink Book) as ‘other payments by households’.</p><p> </p><p>Data for ‘other payments by households’ is available on an annual basis. The 2016 Edition of the Pink Book estimated ‘other payments by households’ at £6.46 billion. (<a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/releases/unitedkingdombalanceofpaymentsthepinkbook2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/releases/unitedkingdombalanceofpaymentsthepinkbook2016</a>)</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-25T16:58:24.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772043/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772043/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-17","Remittances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount of migrant remittances sent from the UK and the countries to which those remittances have been sent.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","108193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772044","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-23","<p>The National Infrastructure Commission is tasked with providing the government with impartial, expert advice on major long-term infrastructure challenges. The Commission has published six main reports since it was established in October 2015:</p><ul><li><p>‘Transport for a World City’, ‘High Speed North’ and ‘Smart Power’ in March 2016</p></li><li><p>‘Cambridge-Milton Keynes-Oxford Corridor Interim Report’ in November 2016</p></li><li><p>‘Connected Future’ in December 2016.</p></li><li><p>‘Congestion, Capacity, Carbon: Priorities for National Infrastructure’, published in October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission’s final report on the Cambridge – Milton Keynes – Oxford corridor and a study on the impact of new technology on infrastructure productivity will be completed this year.</p><p>The Commission’s first National Infrastructure Assessment, a comprehensive report on the UK’s long-term infrastructure needs with recommendations to government, will be published in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Further details of the Commission’s reports are available on its website: <a href="http://www.nic.org.uk/our-work" target="_blank">www.nic.org.uk/our-work</a></p><p> </p></li></ul>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-23T14:37:57.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772044/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772044/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-17","National Infrastructure Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made on the programme of work of the National Infrastructure Commission; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","108194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772045","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-23","<p>Responsibility for pursuing companies that have not filed PSC information rests with Companies House. Over 97% of active companies have filed PSC information.</p><p>Compliance is Companies House’s primary aim, rather than prosecution. It is taking action to ensure that all companies on the active register report their PSC information. Where companies do not move to comply, Companies House will consider what further action to take. This could lead to investigations being passed to other enforcement agencies who will consider the allegation made and, where appropriate, conduct a criminal investigation, which could lead to prosecution action.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-23T10:50:15.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772045/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772045/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772045/answer/previousversion/16640","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-17","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress has been made by HM Revenue and Customs to pursue companies that have not registered their beneficial ownership with Companies House; and how much has been collected in fines from such companies.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","108184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772048","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-24","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government. The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-24T14:11:56.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772048/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772048/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-17","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 9 October 2017 to Question 10193, whether the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA)has conducted investigative work to assess whether consumer credit providers are complying with FCA rules and ensuring that advertised loan APR rates are being offered to at least 51 per cent of those customers who request them.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","108322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772050","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-26","<p>Local authorities, across the North West and wider UK, are best placed to understand the housing needs in their area. National policy sets out clearly the need for local planning authorities to plan for the housing needs of all members of the community and it is for individual authorities to work closely with key partners and local communities in deciding what type of housing is needed to meet local need.</p><p>Supported housing supports many vulnerable people, including those with disabilities, to live independently. That is why we have committed to providing £400 million of funding announced in the Department for Communities and Local Government’s Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme 2016-2021 to deliver affordable homes for the vulnerable, elderly and those with disabilities. Furthermore, the Department of Health has committed £224.5 million to date through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund.</p><p>We have also increased funding for the Disabled Facilities Grant which can contribute to the cost of adapting a property for those with a disability or a care need. The Disabled Facilities Grant funding for England for 2017-18 is £431 million. Funding will rise to £468 million next year, and to over £500 million by 2020.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-26T13:23:19.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772050/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772050/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of specially adapted homes in the (a) North West and (b) UK so that people with complex care needs can live independently for longer.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772052","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>The circumstances in which a landlord may obtain possession of a property are governed by various legislative provisions including in the Housing Act 1988, the Housing Act 1985, the Protection from Eviction Act 1977 and the Deregulation Act 2015. Under this legislation, vulnerable tenants and people in receipt of housing benefit have the same protections as other tenants, including against retaliatory eviction.</p><p>A landlord also cannot evict a tenant using a Section 21 notice where the landlord has not complied with certain legal obligations. This includes protecting their tenants’ deposit in a Tenancy Deposit Protection scheme, providing Gas Safety Certificates, and also providing a copy of the Government’s ‘How to Rent’ guide.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-25T15:09:53.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772052/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772052/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Private Rented Housing: Evictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what protections exist for (a) vulnerable tenants and (b) people in receipt of housing benefit from eviction by landlords.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772053","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The information requested is available in Live Table P300 at the following link: <a href="https://emea01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gov.uk%2Fgovernment%2Fstatistical-data-sets%2Flive-tables-on-land-use-change-statistics&amp;data=02%7C01%7Calok.sharma.mp%40parliament.uk%7Cad28939ea113475fce5308d517b00c64%7C1ce6dd9eb3374088be5e8dbbec04b34a%7C0%7C0%7C636440967242433414&amp;sdata=QuicbxI2%2F68xUibQOzeHxbaMRN6fHsBiARCp92LLtqg%3D&amp;reserved=0" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-land-use-change-statistics</a>.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-20T13:55:44.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772053/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772053/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of new dwellings in England were built on previously developed land in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772054","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-26","<p>The Government periodically assesses resourcing requirements for local government as part of each Spending Review. In addition to the package announced at the 2015 Spending Review and the 2017-18 local Government Finance Settlement, the 2017 Spring Budget provided £2 billion of new funding to support social care. As a result of measures introduced by the Government since 2015, councils had access of up to £9.25 billion more dedicated funding for social care in the 3 years to 2019-20.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-26T13:22:28.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772054/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772054/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the level of funding required for local authority spending on social care in the period to 2020.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772055","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Department does not collect the requested information.</p><p>Development cannot be ruled out in high flood risk areas as around 10 per cent of England, including large parts of major cities, such as Hull, Portsmouth and central London are located in these areas, before taking account of the presence of flood defences. All local planning authorities are expected to follow the strict tests set out in national planning policy and guidance, which includes steering development away from high flood risk areas. Where development in flood risk areas is considered, national planning policy is clear that it should be safe, resilient and not increase flood risk elsewhere. We have been clear that new housing should not be permitted in functional floodplains, where water has to flow or be stored in times of flood.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-25T15:11:41.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772055/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772055/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Property Development: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homes have been granted planning permission for building on flood plains in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772057","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>In 2015-16 (the latest date for which data are available), there were an estimated 1.3 million households in owner occupation with a household reference person (HRP) aged 16-34. (S<em>ource: English Housing Survey Mortgagors Report): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-mortgagors" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-mortgagors</a></em></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-25T14:13:25.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772057/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772057/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Owner Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of trends in the number of people under the age of 30 who own their own home since 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772058","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>Data on the number of home fire safety checks made by Fire and Rescue Services (FRSs) in England are published in fire statistics data table 1201 which accompanied the “Fire and rescue authorities: operational statistics bulletin for England 2015 to 2016” – the release is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fire-statistics#fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics:-latest-version" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fire-statistics#fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics:-latest-version</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-20T09:28:35.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772058/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772058/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many home fire safety checks were completed by fire and rescue services in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16, (c) 2016-17 and (d) 2017 to present.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772059","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-23","<p>Officials have advised that the information requested can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The V5C/3 section of the Registration Certificate is used by a registered keeper to notify the DVLA of the disposal of a vehicle to a motor trader. The DVLA can write to, and take enforcement action against, those who fail to notify disposal of a vehicle.</p><p> </p><p>However, over the last five years, more than 32 million people have notified the disposal of a vehicle to the motor trade by submitting a V5C/3 to the DVLA.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-23T12:43:24.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772059/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-17","Motor Vehicles: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions the DVLA has (a) written to or contacted and (b) initiated legal proceedings against sellers of motor vehicles for failing to use form V5C/3 to notify the DVLA of the transfer of a vehicle to a new owner in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772060","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>As we set out in the Housing White Paper <em>Fixing our broken housing market</em> too few places have an up-to-date plan. At the end of September 2017, 71 (21 per cent) of the 338 local planning authorities had not yet adopted a Local Plan despite having had over twelve years to do so. Of these 71 authorities there are 36 (11 per cent) who still need to submit a plan and a further 29 (9 per cent) who still need to publish. Since the National Planning Policy Framework was published five years ago in March 2012 186 (55 per cent) of authorities have not adopted a new plan.</p><p>The Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017 put beyond doubt the requirement for all areas to be covered by a plan. Proposals in the Housing White Paper <em>Fixing our broken housing market</em> will make plans easier to produce and emphasise the importance of keeping them up to date</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-01T16:21:10.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772060/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772060/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of local planning authorities in England have not (a) published, (b) submitted and (c) adopted a local plan as of October 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772062","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (England) Regulations came into force on 1 October 2015. Local authorities are responsible for enforcement and the Department does not collect information on the number of penalties issued.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","108118","2017-10-25T14:54:07.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772062/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772062/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Private Rented Housing: Alarms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many private sector landlords were fined for failing to comply with the Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (England) Regulations 2015 in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772063","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (England) Regulations came into force on 1 October 2015. Local authorities are responsible for enforcement and the Department does not collect information on the number of penalties issued.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","108117","2017-10-25T14:54:07.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772063/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772063/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Private Rented Housing: Alarms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many private sector landlords were found not to meet the guidelines outlined in the Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (England) Regulations 2015 in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772064","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-30","<p>From January to September 2016, Local Enterprise Partnerships reported that Enterprise Zones had attracted 9,324 new jobs. Monitoring data for the remainder of 2016 will be published later this year.</p><p>Local Enterprise Partnerships report that in total, Enterprise Zones have attracted more than 35,000 jobs across England since April 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-10-30T17:00:58.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772064/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772064/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Enterprise Zones: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many new jobs have been created by enterprise zones since 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772065","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Tenancy Deposit Protection legislation introduced by the Housing Act 2004 requires that where a deposit is paid in connection with an assured shorthold tenancy it must be protected by the landlord or agent in one of the three government-authorised schemes.</p><p>The Tenancy Deposit Schemes in England currently protect over 3.5 million deposits on behalf of tenants, helping to raise standards in the private rented sector and ensuring that tenants are treated fairly at the end of their tenancy.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-25T14:10:07.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772065/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772065/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to protect tenants' monies in tenancy deposit schemes.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","108192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772067","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Government is aware of the change in the Valuation Office Agency’s approach to assessing units within buildings of multiple occupation, following the Supreme Court judgement in the Mazars v Woolway case. The Government is considering the implications of this judgement.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:15:13.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772067/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772067/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure small businesses working in separate parts of a building linked by communal staircases, lifts and corridors do not have those spaces classed as separate premises by the Valuation Office when business rates are being assessed.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","108201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772068","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the answer I gave to Question UIN 3273 on 10 July 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-27T11:28:37.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772068/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772068/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772068/answer/previousversion/16615","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the Government's policy is on implementing a right to buy scheme for tenants of housing association properties in England.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","108167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772069","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>My department committed to fund all 50 eligible local authorities affected by the winter 2015 floods, mainly in the North of England. This includes three upper tier counties who administer grants on behalf of their districts. Out of the 47 authorities issuing grants to flooded householders and businesses under the Community and Business Recovery Scheme, 13 have now closed their recovery schemes. 34 are still disbursing grants to claimants. Any balancing payments due to these authorities will be made after final applications have been received.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-10-25T15:00:36.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772069/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772069/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Floods: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and which local authorities his Department committed to fund as part of the recovery effort for the floods of winter 2015-16; and what proportion of that funding is yet to be paid to each such local authority.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","108231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772071","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>Even one person without a roof over their head is too many. That’s why this Government is investing £550 million to 2020 to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping, as well as implementing the Homelessness Reduction Act, which will require councils to provide early support to people at risk of becoming homeless.</p><p>In some circumstances, the chance to reconnect with their family or friends in another area can help resolve a person's homelessness. But councils should be certain that they are offering someone real help that will resolve their homelessness.</p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of homeless people offered reconnections. More people will be offered help under the homelessness legislation following the commencement of the Homelessness Reduction Act in April 2018. From this point our new data requirements will generate more detailed information about applicants who are referred from one local authority to another for help because of their local connections.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-20T13:52:55.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772071/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772071/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Homelessness: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of homeless people who have been offered a one-way train ticket by local authorities under the policy to reconnect those people with their families between 2012 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","108337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772073","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>Suitable Alternative Natural Greenspace (SANGS) is provided and managed to mitigate harmful effects of new housing developments on European sites protected under the Habitats Regulations 2010. SANGS provides recreational space for local residents, diverting them away from protected sites.</p><p>Where there is limited green space available, Natural England positively encourage the use of existing leisure facilities if they are seen as meeting the requirements to provide Suitable Alternative Natural Greenspace.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-01T17:17:09.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772073/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772073/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Recreation Spaces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to mitigate the potential effects of local planning authorities implementing the Suitable Alternative Natural Green Space policy in urban boroughs where the only green space available is already in use for leisure facilities.","false","Biography information for Leo Docherty","Aldershot","Leo Docherty","108334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772074","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Government is considering how the legislation on Higher Value Assets (HVA) could be implemented under the framework set out in the Housing and Planning Act 2016. Local authorities will not be expected to make an HVA payment in 2017/18.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-20T13:39:34.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772074/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772074/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to proceed with the forced sale of council homes and other assets in order to fund the right to buy programme.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","108213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772076","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-25","<p>On 10 November last year my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government , along with the Home Secretary and the Minister for Vulnerable Children, wrote to local authorities to alert them to potential help regarding unaccompanied asylum seeking children from the Controlling Migration Fund. The Fund fulfils a manifesto commitment to help areas facing challenges linked to recent migration and is able to help with issues such as training for social workers who may be helping these young people.</p><p>We wrote again on 28 March this year outlining a first stage payment of £2 million to authorities supporting those arriving. We will announce later this year further payments to areas which have bid for specific projects looking to boost sustainable capacity in local authorities caring for unaccompanied asylum seeking children.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-25T14:52:05.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772076/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772076/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding his Department has allocated to local authorities to support child refugees.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772077","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>Estimates of the numbers of homes built on flood plains can be obtained by comparing the percentage of new residential addresses created that were in in National Flood Zone 3 with the new build completion statistics. These figures are available for 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 from:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/573278/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/573278/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables.xlsx</a> (Table P320); and</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/568411/LiveTable_120.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/568411/LiveTable_120.xls</a> (Table 120)</p><p>Figures for previous years exist only for 2011 and earlier years and are not on the same basis as those in Table P320.</p><p>All local planning authorities are expected to follow the strict tests set out in national planning policy and guidance, which includes steering development away from high flood risk areas. Where development in flood risk areas is considered, national planning policy is clear that it should be safe, resilient and not increase flood risk elsewhere.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-13T16:35:32.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772077/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772077/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-17","Property Development: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homes have been built on flood plains in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772078","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>Ofcom consulted on a Help Scheme for Programme Makers and Special Events earlier this year. Government is awaiting Ofcom’s assessment of responses to that consultation, with a final decision on the Help scheme yet to be taken.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","108230","2017-10-25T10:07:35.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772078/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772078/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Broadcasting: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the reason was for the decision to restrict the Programme Making and Special Events funding scheme to the residual value of equipment.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","108229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772079","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>Ofcom consulted on a Help Scheme for Programme Makers and Special Events earlier this year. Government is awaiting Ofcom’s assessment of responses to that consultation, with a final decision on the Help scheme yet to be taken.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","108229","2017-10-25T10:07:35.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772079/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772079/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Broadcasting: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with Ofcom on the non-equipment costs to businesses in the Programme Making and Special Events sector as a result of the clearance of the 700 MHz band.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","108230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772081","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>We recognise the importance of the Programme Makers and Special Events industry to the entertainment sector and the wider UK economy. We will be providing Government funded support to the PMSE industry through the 700MHz spectrum clearance programme, aimed at mitigating the impacts on the industry and enabling them to continue to provide high quality services to the entertainment industry after spectrum clearance.</p><p> </p><p>Following Ofcom advice to Government, Ofcom consulted on a Help Scheme to provide support to the industry. We are awaiting Ofcom’s assessment of responses to this consultation and a decision on the level of support will be made once this has been taken into account.</p><p> </p><p>To further mitigate impacts on the industry, and provide the possibility for future growth, Ofcom has also decided to allocate frequencies in the 960-1164MHz band for PMSE.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","108228 ; 108356","2017-10-25T15:04:41.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772081/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772081/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the effect on the live entertainment sector in terms of production value and economic cost as a result of the decision to clear the 700 MHz radio spectrum band.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","108233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772082","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Department does not hold information on broadband speed as a constituency average. Currently in the hon member's constituency, according to Thinkbroadband, 94.3% of premises have access to Superfast coverage.</p><p>Information on Superfast coverage is available from third party sites like Think Broadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/uk).</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-25T10:01:41.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772082/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772082/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, which parts of the UK have the (a) fastest and (b) slowest broadband speeds.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","108354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772083","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>We are supporting investment in superfast and basic broadband through the Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) Programme. BDUK has a comprehensive project assurance system in place and Government funding is only committed when a contract is fit for purpose. All contracts are proactively managed through the BDUK Programme and, if necessary, robust contractual mechanisms can be applied if contractual commitments are not met.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-25T10:03:45.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772083/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772083/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how the Government holds to account broadband providers that fail to meet their agreed commitments.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","108355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772085","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>There are strong protections in place against operators of illegal gambling facilities, including within video games. All operators providing gambling services to consumers in Britain require a licence from the Gambling Commission and must adhere to strict requirements for the protection of children and the vulnerable. The Gambling Commission has also commissioned the Responsible Gambling Strategy Board to examine the wider relationship between children and gambling.</p><p>In addition, consumers are protected by the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008. This includes a requirement on businesses not to subject anyone to misleading or aggressive marketing practices, or, for example, direct exhortation to buy products, such as games content, including in-game purchases such as loot boxes. The government is committed to ensuring that consumers are properly protected and that children’s vulnerability and inexperience is not exploited by aggressive commercial practices.</p><p>The government’s Internet Safety Strategy sets out how the government will work with online platforms, game publishers and game developers, and with agencies such as the VSC Rating Board, to continue to improve online safety in games.</p><p>The government recognises the risks that come from increasing convergence between gambling and video games. The Gambling Commission is keeping this matter under review and will continue to monitor developments in the market.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-25T11:24:52.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772085/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772085/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Gambling: Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2017 to Question 106042, what discussions she has had with her Cabinet colleagues on adopting protections against illegal and in-game gambling and loot boxes.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","108321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772086","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>Neither the Department nor the Gambling Commission hold information concerning the number of Fixed-Odds Betting Terminals and, therefore spend in individual constituencies.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-25T11:27:18.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772086/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772086/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Gaming Machines: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an estimate of the amount spent each year on fixed-odds betting terminals in Glasgow East constituency.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","108095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772087","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-19","<p>Current advertising restrictions in the UK on high fat, salt or sugar (HFSS) products are among the toughest in the world. Strict new rules came into effect on 1 July banning the advertising of HFSS food or drink products in children’s media. These restrictions apply across all non-broadcast media including in print, cinema, online and in social media.</p><p> </p><p>In August we announced £5 million investment to fund a national institute for obesity research policy unit to provide a robust evidence base and deeper understanding of the causes of childhood obesity, including marketing to children and families. The unit’s findings will be fed into the department's future policy development and engagement.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","107438 ; 107444","2017-10-19T12:10:22.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772087/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772087/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-17","Food: Marketing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the effect on children's health of restricting the marketing of high in fat, salt or sugar foods before the 9pm watershed.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","108086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772089","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-24","<p>Final decisions have not yet been taken on BAE Systems’ consultation on transforming its business. However the Government remains engaged with BAE Systems to understand the impact of the potential job reductions, and to ensure that vital skills are maintained.</p><p>This Government recognises the strength and capability of the UK's aerospace sector. We have a substantial programme of work underway through the Defence Growth Partnership, which is identifying opportunities to encourage growth and competitiveness of the UK defence sector. Taken alongside the Future Combat Air Systems Technology Initiative, this will maintain and enhance the UK's position as a global leader in combat air technologies.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-24T12:09:18.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772089/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772089/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772089/answer/previousversion/16617","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-17","BAE Systems: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of BAE Systems job losses, announced in October 2017, on the UK's capacity to produce aircraft and aviation systems.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","108110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772090","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-20","<p>There are currently 14 Hawk T1 aircraft with the Royal Air Force Aerobatic Team (RAFAT). This provides spare capacity should any display aircraft develop faults or require routine maintenance. The flying hours accrued by each individual aircraft during its lifetime are given below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Individual</strong> <strong>Aircraft</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Flying Hours</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX177</p></td><td><p>8,450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX204</p></td><td><p>8,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX227</p></td><td><p>8,030</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX232</p></td><td><p>8,680</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX242</p></td><td><p>9,530</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX244</p></td><td><p>10,490</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX245</p></td><td><p>10,130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX278</p></td><td><p>8,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX310</p></td><td><p>8,660</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX311</p></td><td><p>8,390</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX319</p></td><td><p>7,240</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX322</p></td><td><p>7,210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX323</p></td><td><p>6,670</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>XX325</p></td><td><p>8,860</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures provided are as at 16 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>RAFAT rotates its aircraft within the general Hawk T1 fleet of 75 aircraft and therefore the hours shown will not all have been accrued with RAFAT.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-20T13:53:34.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772090/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772090/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Hawk Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many flying hours the nine Hawk aircraft of the Royal Aircraft Aerobatics Team have flown since they were introduced.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","108180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772092","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is aware of media reports that Sally Jones and her son, Joe Dixon, were killed in a drone strike in Syria in June. The FCO does not comment on security matters.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-20T13:46:29.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772092/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772092/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-17","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterparts on the reported death of Joe Dixon as a result of a drone strike in Syria.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","108164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772093","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is aware of media reports that Sally Jones and her son, Joe Dixon, were killed in a drone strike in Syria in June. The FCO does not comment on security matters.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-20T13:47:21.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772093/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772093/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-17","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will confirm whether Sally Jones and Joe Dixon were killed in a drone strike; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","108165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772094","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering's (DSME) financial issues emerged in 2016, four years after the contract for the Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tanker programme was placed.</p><p>The Department held no information regarding potential corruption or accounting irregularities with DSME at the time of contract award for the MARS programme in 2012.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-25T13:42:46.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772094/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772094/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Royal Fleet Auxiliary: Tankers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department held on potential corruption or accounting issues with Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering at the time of placing orders for the Tide-class of tankers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772095","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>We expect all four Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers to have entered service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary by the end of 2018, as planned.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","108304","2017-10-25T13:39:40.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772095/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772095/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Royal Fleet Auxiliary: Tankers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) estimated original planned date of entry into service was and (b) current expected date for entry into service is for each of the planned Tide-class tankers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772096","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>We expect all four Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers to have entered service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary by the end of 2018, as planned.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","108303","2017-10-25T13:39:40.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772096/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772096/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Royal Fleet Auxiliary: Tankers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons the first two Tide-class tankers have been delivered behind schedule.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772098","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>Each year, the Ministry of Defence awards a significant number of contracts, by means of both single source and competitive procurement. Procurers have to assess whether the issues set out in National Security Objective 3, which seeks to promote our prosperity, are relevant to their procurement. As each contract is awarded on its own merit, detailed information is held with individual commercial teams and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","108301","2017-10-25T13:35:36.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772098/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772098/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what weight was attached to the marking criteria for National Security Objective 3 for each of his Department's contracts for which that objective was taken into account.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772099","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>Each year, the Ministry of Defence awards a significant number of contracts, by means of both single source and competitive procurement. Procurers have to assess whether the issues set out in National Security Objective 3, which seeks to promote our prosperity, are relevant to their procurement. As each contract is awarded on its own merit, detailed information is held with individual commercial teams and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","108302","2017-10-25T13:35:36.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772099/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772099/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and which of his Department's contracts placed since the 2015 SDSR, whose value is £1 million or above, have taken National Security Objective 3 into account.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772100","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>We currently have no plans to increase the number of UK personnel assigned to UN Command Korea, but we routinely review our commitment to international headquarters and missions around the region.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-25T13:41:48.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772100/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772100/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","United Nations Command: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to increase the number of UK armed forces personnel assigned to UN Command.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772101","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>For financial year 2017-18, £249,000 per annum has been allocated to fund two staff officer positions within UN Command in the Republic of Korea.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-25T13:42:15.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772101/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772101/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","United Nations Command","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the estimated cost to his Department is of the UK's annual contribution to UN Command.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772103","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>In view of the scale and lack of transparency of the recent Zapad 17 exercise led by Russia, the UK and its Allies remained vigilant throughout. A variety of means were used to monitor the conduct of the exercise. I cannot comment further for the purpose of safeguarding national security.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-25T13:36:08.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772103/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772103/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","Russia: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to announce the results of the UK element of the surveillance operation to monitor Zapad 17; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","108300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772104","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-25","<p>The numbers of UK Armed Forces personnel that have been sent to exercises KEY RESOLVE and ULCHI FREEDOM GUARDIAN held under the United Nations Command in Republic of Korea in each of the last five years is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>KEY RESOLVE</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>ULCHI FREEDOM GUARDIAN</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Navy</p></td><td><p>Army</p></td><td><p>RAF</p></td><td><p>Navy</p></td><td><p>Army</p></td><td><p>RAF</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-25T13:43:57.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772104/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772104/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-17","United Nations Command: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK armed forces personnel from the (a) Royal Navy, (b) Army and (c) Royal Air Force have been sent to the two annual exercises held under the UN Command in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham",