"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772239","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>The published information on processing times for visa applications is published as part of the Migration Transparency data, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-25T16:07:46.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772239/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772239/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Visas: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) average and (b) longest waiting time was for non-straightforward Tier 5 visa applications in each quarter of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","108188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772240","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Government is fully committed to tackling domestic abuse and stalking. The Home Office has met and continues to meet with a number of partners to develop proposals to further protect victims and further target perpetrators, which have included discussions on the introduction of a register.</p><p> </p><p>Those convicted of domestic abuse related offences and stalking offences are already captured on the Police National Computer. Where appropriate, they will also be captured on other systems such as on the Dangerous Persons’ Database, and managed by police and probation under Multi-agency Public Protection Arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s focus is on ensuring we make better use of existing</p><p>systems, rather than creating new databases or registers for different</p><p>offences, which risks a disjointed police and offender management response.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Domestic Violence Disclosure Scheme has also been rolled out nationally to inform and alert new partners about a perpetrator's previous offending.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-24T14:05:38.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772240/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772240/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Domestic Abuse: Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on the introduction of a register for people found guilty of stalking or domestic violence offences.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","108200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772241","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Section 13 of the Criminal Finances Act allows for civil recovery to be undertaken in cases in relation to property connected with gross human rights abuse or violations. It expands the definition of 'unlawful conduct' within Part 5 of the Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) to include conduct by a public official that constitutes gross human rights abuse or violations (defined as torture or inhuman, cruel or degrading treatment) of a person on the grounds that they have been obtaining, exercising, defending or promoting human rights, or have sought to expose gross human rights abuse conducted by a public official.</p><p>This new power also covers conduct occurring anywhere in the world, provided that it would constitute a sufficiently serious offence if it had occurred in the UK (i.e. that it would have been triable by indictment).</p><p>There are a number of dependencies which must be implemented before the Act, including section 13, can be commenced. Work is underway, to ensure the necessary court rules, secondary legislation, training, guidance, and human resources are in place for commencement of the Act by Summer 2018. This includes the guidance for prosecutors and investigators issued under Section 2A of POCA.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-10-24T15:42:12.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772241/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772241/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Proceeds of Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will communicate guidance to the Director-General of the National Crime Agency on the use of the powers under section 241A of the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002, as amended by Criminal Finances Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","108203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772243","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>On 14 October we launched a public consultation on new legislation on offensive and dangerous weapons. This includes the proposal that where a knife is sold online it is an offence to deliver the knife to a private residential address. This is intended to apply to online sales of knives so we can prevent knives being sold to under 18s online. However, the proposal will not prevent knives being sold online and instead being collected from a place where the age and identity of the purchaser can be checked or from being delivered to a non-residential address such as a business. We recognise that knives are essential in everyday life at home and at work and this proposal does not change that.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-24T14:01:59.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772243/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772243/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Knives: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether people who purchase knives for work-related purposes will be made exempt from the proposed ban on online knife sales.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","108102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772246","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office (HM Passport Office) needs to be satisfied with an applicant’s claim to nationality, identity and entitlement to issue a passport. The absence of a birth certificate in itself does not preclude the issue of a passport and applications are assessed on a case by case basis considering the information and alternative documents available.</p><p>Where no documentation is available, there is provision within the British Nationality legislation for a person to register as a British citizen, this will depend on the requirements for registration.</p><p>If the enquiry relates to a specific case, I would encourage my honourable friend from Torbay to write to HM Passport Office to discuss how the matter can be resolved.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-30T07:24:34.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772246/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772246/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what provisions she has put in place for people who grew up in care and are unable to provide a birth certificate when applying for a passport.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","108350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772248","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes statistics on the number of police officers employed by each police force in England and Wales on a bi-annual basis. These data are published in the ‘Police workforce, England and Wales’ statistical bulletins, which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The Home Office does not collect this information at borough level. Data on the number of police officers in Metropolitan Police Service, as at 31 March each year, can be found in the Open Data Tables accompanying the main release: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/629362/open-data-table-police-workforce.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/629362/open-data-table-police-workforce.ods</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-20T09:20:23.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772248/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772248/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Metropolitan Police: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of police officers in the Metropolitan Police Service worked in the London Borough of Newham in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","108252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772249","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Home Office does not currently publish data on unaccompanied migrant children’s movements between local authorities in its quarterly statistics release.</p><p>The published data on unaccompanied asylum seeking children can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to#unaccompanied-asylum-seeking-children" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to#unaccompanied-asylum-seeking-children</a>.</p><p>There are over 4,000 unaccompanied asylum seeking children (UASC) in local authority care in the UK. The National Transfer Scheme was launched on 1 July 2016 and has been working to ensure a fairer allocation of UASC across the UK. A significant number of local authorities have participated in the scheme and enabled the transfer of children away from local authorities with a disproportionate number of UASC in their care.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-20T13:58:04.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772249/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772249/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unaccompanied migrant children in the UK have been moved to at least two different local authorities since their arrival.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","108253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772250","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>At March 2016, standalone Fire Authorities held reserves of £602m. This is an increase of 153% since March 2010, and represents 43% of core spending power in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Communities and Local Government collects and publishes data on revenue expenditure and financing of local authorities in England, including financial reserve levels. Final outturn information for 2015/16 can be found on the Government website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-individual-local-authority-data-outturn" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-individual-local-authority-data-outturn</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-24T15:37:38.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772250/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772250/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Fire and Rescue Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment has been made of the adequacy of the level of financial reserves held by fire authorities.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","108234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772251","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The primary responsibility for unaccompanied children in France lies with the French government. Following the closure of the Calais Camp, French authorities transferred all children formerly resident to specialist centres across France. It is vital that children claim asylum in France; that is the fastest route to safety.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have a strong track record of cooperating with France to manage the situation in Calais and to protect our shared border. We supported the humanitarian operation to clear the Calais migrant camp in October 2016, which involved the transfer of more than 750 children to the UK and funding to help provide migrants in Calais – including children – with suitable facilities elsewhere in France. Our law enforcement agencies work closely together to</p><p>tackle smuggling and trafficking. Home Office officials meet with their French colleagues on a regular basis.</p><p> </p><p>According to Eurostat data, 63,300 unaccompanied children claimed asylum in the EU in 2016:</p><p><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/8016696/3-11052017-AP-EN.pdf/30ca2206-0db9-4076-a681-e069a4bc5290" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/8016696/3-11052017-AP-EN.pdf/30ca2206-0db9-4076-a681-e069a4bc5290</a></p><p> </p><p>This includes a breakdown of asylum applications by EU Member State.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-20T13:58:26.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772251/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772251/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of closing the refugee camp in Calais on the availability of data on unaccompanied child refugees; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","108251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772253","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>The published information on processing times for visa applications is published as part of the Migration Transparency data, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-25T16:08:14.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772253/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772253/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) average and (b) longest waiting time was for non-straightforward Tier 4 visa applications in each quarter of each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","108208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772255","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The published information on processing times for visa applications is published as part of the Migration Transparency data, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-operations-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-20T09:21:06.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772255/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772255/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) average and (b) longest waiting time was for non-straightforward spousal visa applications in each quarter of each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","108209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772256","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>The requested data can be found here:</p><p><em> </em></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/border-force-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/border-force-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>If 95% or above of passenger wait times sampled are recorded as within the 25 minute (EEA) and 45 minute (non EEA) service standard, the service level is assessed as met, if less than 95%, then this is considered a breach of the service level.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent published data is for Q1 2017 and shows Border Force performance at 98.5%.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","108211","2017-10-25T16:07:05.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772256/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772256/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Immigration Controls: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average waiting time was at immigration control at the 10 busiest airports in the summer months of each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","108210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772258","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>The requested data can be found here:</p><p><em> </em></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/border-force-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/border-force-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>If 95% or above of passenger wait times sampled are recorded as within the 25 minute (EEA) and 45 minute (non EEA) service standard, the service level is assessed as met, if less than 95%, then this is considered a breach of the service level.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent published data is for Q1 2017 and shows Border Force performance at 98.5%.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","108210","2017-10-25T16:07:05.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772258/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772258/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-17","Immigration Controls: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average waiting times are at immigration control at the 10 busiest airports in the UK in peak morning and evening arrivals.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","108211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772259","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-24","<p>The table (below) shows DFID’s financial contributions to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria over the timeframe specified.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>£ millions</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>285</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>153</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-24T16:38:22.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772259/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772259/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funds her Department has committed to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria programme in the financial years (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","108242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772260","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-24","<p>DFID supports TB control through both bilateral and multilateral channels. The Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and malaria is the principal mechanism the UK uses to finance our contribution to combat TB. We have pledged up to £1.1 billion for 2017-2019 to this Fund. We also support countries to strengthen their health systems so as to better address all causes of ill health including TB. In addition we support research on TB including to develop more effective diagnostics and treatment.</p><p>Our purely bilateral spending on TB, which we publish by calendar year, is: £7,938,747 for 2013; £16,312,293 for 2014; and £10,017,171 for 2015. Data beyond 2015 has not yet been published.</p><p>Data on UK aid expenditure is published each year and can be accessed from the link below</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2016</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-24T16:46:55.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772260/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772260/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Developing Countries: Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department provided for bilateral programmes on tuberculosis in the financial years (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","108243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772261","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Prosperity Fund has been designed in accordance with the OECD DAC guidelines on Overseas Development Assistance and the 2015 UK Aid Strategy with a primary purpose to support economic development and poverty reduction in developing countries. It is expected that a secondary benefit of strengthening economic development in these countries will be increased trade and investment opportunities, including for UK companies. The Prosperity Fund is overseen by a Ministerial Board, with Minister of State Burt representing DFID, which sets strategic priorities. Official Development Assistance (ODA) eligibility and compliance with the International Development Act are central to Prosperity Fund assessment and approvals processes.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-24T16:51:52.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772261/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772261/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on ensuring that expenditure from the Prosperity Fund prioritises international development over UK industrial and political interests.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","108245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772263","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-23","<p>DFID’s standard terms and conditions require all suppliers to notify DFID of any occasion of tax non-compliance within 5 working days. No current DFID suppliers have been convicted of a breach of obligations relating to the payment of tax in the UK.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-23T17:01:36.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772263/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772263/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Department for International Development: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many companies supplying goods and services to her Department, or contracted to deliver services on behalf of her Department, have been identified as avoiding their tax liabilities in the UK.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","108265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772264","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-20","<p>The UK is at the forefront of responding to the plight of the Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh. As a world leader in humanitarian crises, this is what we do best. We have repeatedly called for better access for NGOs working in Rohingya-populated areas to be allowed access based on merit, and will continue to do so. We are pressing for a clearer, more transparent process for registering NGOs working with the Rohingya in Bangladesh.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-20T13:18:12.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772264/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772264/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Bangladesh: Islamic Relief","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make representations to the Bangladeshi Government on ensuring that Islamic Relief is able to operate in that country; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","108340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772265","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-24","<p>We welcome the recent judgment by the High Court in favour of the Government on UK arms sales to Saudi Arabia, which underscores the fact that the UK operates one of the most robust export control regimes in the world. We will continue to keep our defence exports under careful review to ensure they meet the rigorous standards of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p><p>The UN assesses Yemen to be the world’s largest humanitarian crisis. Nearly 21 million people are in need of humanitarian aid. DFID’s support of £155 million for 2017-8 will feed 1.8 million people for at least a month, and provide 1.7 million people with nutrition support and an expected 1.2 million people with clean water and sanitation. We continue to strongly support the work of the UN’s Special Envoy to Yemen, Ismail Ould Cheikh Ahmed, to end the conflict and bring about peace.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-24T16:13:47.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772265/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772265/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-17","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of arms sales to Saudi Arabia on development and humanitarian outcomes in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","108139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772266","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-25","<p>The table below sets out the staff allocation to the Central London County Court in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Budgeted Resources</p></td><td><p>Central London staff allocation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-18</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16-17</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15-16</p></td><td><p>64</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14-15</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13-14</p></td><td><p>56.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-25T16:25:38.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772266/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772266/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","County Courts: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what resources have been allocated to the Central London County Court in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","108149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772268","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-25","<p>The county courts are primarily staffed by multi-skilled administrative grades who are moved around the office as and when the need arises. Managers will use their discretion as to the skills and experience of staff members when allocating which administrative process they undertake.</p><p>Administrative staff resource is allocated using the Business Management System (BMS). This is a workload management tool which captures the workflow through the Court. It enables managers to keep track of changing priorities and allocate resources to meet them.</p><p>The system does not take away a manager’s discretion to take into account local factors and redistribute allotted resources in a way which maximises service in Court, but the effect of such decisions will be transparent and measurable.</p><p>In court support is agreed with the local judiciary once the financial allocation is made to best support them and the administration of justice.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-25T16:26:37.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772268/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772268/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","County Courts: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how staffing resources are allocated within the Central London County Court.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","108150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772269","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Government is considering the planned post-implementation review of recent legal aid reforms and we will make an announcement in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-20T13:40:25.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772269/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772269/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to commence its review of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","108159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772270","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>From the inception of the Exceptional Case Funding (ECF) scheme in April 2013, there have been no applications for ECF either lodged or granted for clinical negligence claims relating to vaginal mesh implants.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-20T12:28:27.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772270/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772270/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for exceptional case funding were (a) made and (b) granted for clinical negligence where the case relates to vaginal mesh implants in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","108187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772271","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>Since 2015, the Government has invested £5 million of funding to support litigants in person through a range of measures designed to provide practical support and information, as well as providing routes to free or more affordable legal advice services.</p><p>The Government is considering the planned post-implementation review of recent legal aid reforms and we will make an announcement in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-20T13:40:45.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772271/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772271/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which options the Government plans to assess on reducing the number of litigants in person as part of its review into the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","108161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772273","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Government is considering the planned post-implementation review of recent legal aid reforms and we will make an announcement in due course.</p><p>We are aware that previous Ministers agreed to submit a post-legislative memorandum for the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act to Parliament and to begin a post-implementation review of recent legal aid reforms shortly afterward. We are also aware that the Government has had a long-standing commitment to doing this review and publishing it by April 2018.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-20T13:41:05.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772273/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772273/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which provisions of the Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 the Government's plans to scrutinise in its post-implementation review.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","108162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772274","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-20T12:28:38.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772274/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/772274/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-17","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many clinical negligence proceedings involving the death of a child were granted legal aid in (a) 2008, (b) 2009, (c) 2010, (d) 2011, (e) 2012 and (f) 2013.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","108186"
